00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
should we fix the microbiome in allotransplant recipients? Let's consider these two scenarios.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.460
In both scenarios, things that we do before and early after transplant, such as antibiotics,

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:21.400
chemoradiation as part of the conditioning, nutritional changes, these will cause disruptions

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:29.000
to the gut microbiome, which we collectively know as dysbiosis. Now, in scenario one,

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:35.160
it's this dysbiosis that will directly cause some of the bad outcomes that we see after transplant,

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:42.920
whereas in the other scenario, dysbiosis is simply a surrogate for the fact that there's

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:47.840
a lot going on with that patient, and maybe it's those things that caused the bad outcomes,

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:53.020
not dysbiosis itself. Now, why is this distinction important? It's because

00:00:53.020 --> 00:00:58.920
it's only in the first scenario that fixing the gut microbiome has a potential to improve

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:06.920
outcomes. But in either scenario, you would find an association, which could be very, very strong,

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:15.640
between dysbiosis and outcomes. It won't exceed an association if it was a non-causal relationship.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:27.340
So let's see if we even know for sure there is an association, let alone the causality. So the largest

