00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:58.640
then be able to prevent GVHD perhaps? And so we attempted two different strategies. One was by just

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:04.460
simply increasing the dose of the microbiome in the next trial. And also we compared three different

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:12.220
donors, stool donors, to see if one was particularly more potent in engrafting their microbiome in the

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:20.760
patient. And we found both. With this increased dose, the engraftment rate went up by about 25%. And also

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:50.820
we found that the FMT donor 3, which is shown on the top, was distinctly better than the other two donors in terms of engraftment. And then in the randomized phase of this trial, the product, the FMT product, is being manufactured only from this winner donor. And it's being compared to placebo with a clinical endpoint of grade 3 to 4 GVHD. It's double blind, placebo controlled. And we've completed enrollment, randomization. Hopefully we will have some data at ASH. So my conclusions are I think the effect size is probably

00:07:50.820 --> 00:08:01.200
small for microbiome. That's why we see a lot of inconsistencies. And that's why in the complex human setting, randomized trials are the only path forward. Thank you.
